segments.text: Today's date is July 1, 1981.
This is a test.
This is Terry Anderson.
There we go.
This is an interview with Major General William Becker.
Today is 1st July, 1981.
This is Terry Anderson.
Let's start with your parents.
Could you tell me about your parents, your mother and father?
Yes.
My father, whose name was George Becker, was born here on this land where we live now.
In the old house over here?
No, he moved to the old home here when he was two.
It was built when he was two years old.
His grandfather had come here from Germany, and the family history is that William Ernest Becker had fled Germany.
He was a political refugee of some sort.
When?
Back in 1834.
I believe it was 1834.
He had a rather responsible position.
And it was obviously a political position.
He was in charge of the, what was his name, William, the emperor's?
Wilhelm.
Wilhelm.
Frederick Wilhelms.
Game preserves throughout Germany.
And I say that had to be a political appointment, because he majored in music at the University of Berlin.
No kidding.
But anyway, he came over here and brought his family.
We still have at home there some of the items of furniture they brought, which wasn't much.
I still have the old gun.
By the way, I meant to show you that that he brought over from Germany, because you mentioned you're interested in guns.
And he stopped first in Pennsylvania and moved on west after a few years to Illinois and looked for greener pastures down here and came here in 1848.
Bought some land here and then expanded upon it.
And then, of course, his children stayed in the area and married in the area.

I say that I'm kin to any family that's within horseback riding distance from here, I'm kin to if they've been here over 60 years, because that was about the courting distance, you know, in those days.
My grandfather became sort of the one that stayed in the center of the land, so to speak, and then my father succeeding him.
And my father tried to retain or reacquire as much of the family land as he could.
He did a pretty good job of it, I think, considering the years of the Depression and all that sort of thing.
My grandfather, of course, married a neighbor girl.
My father married my mother, who was the daughter of the Methodist minister in Kauffman.
who had earlier been ministering Kemp.
And after their ministry in Kauffman, Mother had completed college and had returned to Kauffman as a schoolteacher.
Oh, really?
Where'd she go to college?
She went to Kidd Key College, which no longer exists.
It was over at Greenville.
Kidd Key?
How do you go there?
K-I-d-d-d-k-e-y.
Oh, I've never even heard of that.
But it's been off the map for some time.
And of course, that's where Dad met her.
Was he over there going to college, too?
No.
He met her in Coppin when she came to teach school.
And they married, and he brought her to the country.
So she had an education degree then.
Yes, she had a teacher's certificate.
Actually, I believe in those days the only requirement, I think Kidd Key, as a matter of fact, I'm not certain of this, was a two-year school.
And I think that was the requirement in those days to be certificated, certified.
And she taught just a few years before Dad brought her out here.
And they had six children, five boys and a girl, the girl being next to the youngest.
George, the old George Jr., the oldest, has been here all through the years.
My dad died by accident in 1948.
And mother died in 1975.
George has been here through the years.
He's been in the cattle business and real estate business.
And he's had a very interesting life.
been in a very interesting aspect of real estate.
He has been the land man, so to speak, for the acquisition of land for a number of the lakes that have been built by the Sabine River Authority.
Like, for example, this, what do they call it, the new lake over near Quitman that Dallas is about to acquire.
Oh, yeah.
And what he's done is go in and make an estimate of what it's going to cost to acquire the land.
In that case, I think it was 40,000 acres.
And then he sets about acquiring it.
And it's a very complex and interesting operation, but we won't get too far off on that.
But anyway, Georgia stayed here.
Walter, the next brother, became a general surgeon, spent most of his professional life at New Orleans.
He was a graduate of TCU and then Vanderbilt.
Vanderbilt Medical School.
George, by the way, graduated from Texas A&M in 37.
And Brother Walter died in February this year.
Then I was the next one.
Of course, I went to A&M.
And then Brother Young and I had a Navy career.
He retired, I guess, three years ago as a rear admiral in the Navy.
And he died last fall.
The sister, the only sister, interestingly enough, married our Methodist minister.
And I might add that all these boys gave him some trouble during those serious courtship months.
We thought we didn't want a preacher for a brother-in-law, I guess.
And that our grandfather had been
close to the fire, you know.
What about the youngest?
In those years, the Methodist minister was a student at SMU for years to keep our little church going in Kent and here.
So he was a graduating student when they met, but he's a very fine man.
What about the youngest?
The youngest is an architect, lives in Dallas.
He graduated from Yale and did his initial
professional practice in New Haven and came to Dallas later.
So that's the family to me.
And would you like our lineup within the family?
Well, I'd like to know about your father's education.
Your great-grandfather was one of the few people in Germany that went to university.
Very few people in the 1800s went to university.
And then you did, of course, too, in America.
your father and your grandfather also go to a university?
No, no.
My grandfather did not, nor did my father.
Of course, my grandfather stayed on the land here, and so did Dad.
Dad was, uh, left school in the, he finished the tenth grade, and he lost his father, and, uh, when he was young, and he had the responsibility for his mother,
and his baby sister.
So he didn't even finish high school.
But I consider him a very well-educated man.
Well, what kind of man was your father?
Can you tell me?
Can you describe him?
Well, in appearance, he was tall and very active.
And matter of fact, he was 69 years old when he was accidentally killed.
And he could still work me down when I'd come home and help him do whatever.
I think he was very well read.
He was a leader in the community and the area.
As a matter of fact, I think that during the Depression, he was the director of the Federal Land Bank of this district, and he was, I think, a charter director of the
production credit associations when they were created, the local one or the area one.
I think it was headquartered in McKinney.
But I mention this because the Depression took a heavy toll of land in terms of foreclosures.
I think he really
At least I met some members of the Federal Land Bank staff that told me he'd been very instrumental in the policy making that saved a lot of those people, but also saved the loans.
Well, he should have been capable in that regard, having been pretty substantial landowner and operator himself.
So you say that he was a leader, and was he like a mayor, or can you define that?
Well, of course, he always lived in the country, and he was involved very heavily in community affairs.
We never had a formal community organization other than school board, of course, and he was seen to be forever on the school board.
But he was very...
active, as I mentioned, in the farm organizations of all kinds and in this financing field.
Was he active in the church?
He was active in the church, and Mother, of course, was very active in the church.
But he spent a lot of time around this county and this area just doing things for the public good, and so people respected him for it.
He never ran for elective office, I guess, other than...
school board.
Mother, of course, was a homemaker and a great mother and a great supporter of Dad and that partnership.
Would you consider that religion then was important in your upbringing?
I think it was very important.
I've never been a very demonstrative person in terms of religion, but of course, Mother being the daughter of a Methodist minister, we had certainly the benefit of good training.
And when I've needed it, it's been very important to me.
And, you know, you do need it from time to time.
When you feel you need it, you need to call on the strengths that religion gives.
Now, in your home when you were growing up, who was the authority?
Well, there's no question.
Dad was the supreme authority, but it was sort of... Supreme commander.
Yeah.
But Mother tried to handle all...
old thing because she was always there but if she couldn't she'd she'd refer it to the higher authority and so we had pretty good discipline in this family of ours.
He was a disciplinarian would you say?
I would say so very strict one.
He was strict?
Yeah.
How'd you get along with your brothers and your one sister?
Oh we got along fine I think we had uh we had the usual
squabbles with the next older and the next younger.
I was between boys.
The sister got along famously, but it was a little bit difficult for her to grow up with five boys.
I would imagine.
But she was none the worse for it.
We, I think, grew to have a great deal of respect for each other, too.
You know, that's important.
I want to check this.
Okay, now you've become a leader and a success making general officer in the United States Army.
In which ways do you think that your parents are responsible for that?
Well, I think, of course, first of all, I knew what disciplined behavior was because I learned it from them firsthand.
And I think...
They also taught us the importance of the objective in life, or next week, or whatever.
And of course, as a matter of fact, the objective is one of the most important principles of war, having a goal, having an objective.
It's kind of hard to accomplish anything significant without it.
And that, I think, was a very important thing.
Leadership, I think, knowledge is a very, very important ingredient or element of leadership.
They insisted it would be good students and good learners.
And of course, when you have that situation, you learn something about what your capacities are.
I think a person who's never tested doesn't know what his capacities are.
Were you tested at home then a lot?
No, I mean, I use that term tested in terms of practical testing, testing by the situation.
Well, that's what I know.
Yeah.
So they insisted that we apply ourselves and we devote good effort to whatever we were doing.
And as my old daddy used to say, anything worth doing is worth doing right.
So they gave us a good foundation, a very good basis.
I never felt that destiny was calling me.
I just always tried to do a good job and try to set some goals and apply myself.
Tell me about your education.
Well, of course, I went to this country school here through the eighth grade, and then I
to Kauffman High School, graduated there in our Texas centennial year in 1936.
I had two brothers in college at the time, George and A&M and Pete and Walter in TCU.
And so I had to wait a year before the family finances could support me.
OK, but before we get to that, tell me what your favorite subjects were while you were in grade and high school.
Well, I don't recall that I had any favorites in grade school.
And we were sort of taught to treat them all alike, you know, excel in all of them.
It's interesting, reading, writing, and arithmetic, we heard a lot of in terms, those terms, when I was going to grade school.
And I don't know that...
arithmetic never was, or math was never my favorite.
I never felt extended in reading and writing, but I did like composition.
We had the interscholastic league meets from the time I entered school through the high school year that you may be familiar with the old pattern, it isn't there anymore.
But this little country school became famous for winning
the rural classification championships in those inter-classics and the league meets nearly every year.
Well, I always won the spelling, so I became, I thought, an accomplished speller through those grades.
But in high school, I was fortunate to have a very strong English department and English teacher and math teacher.
I think any youngster that goes to college then or today finds those are the two things that probably strain him the most.
And if you don't have a good basis, it's difficult.
We got a good basis, I think.
So you were good in math and in English.
I thought I was better in English, but I could handle the math.
Were you a good student?
Oh, I think so.
If I look back on it, I...
I was trying pretty well to do what was expected of me when I was in grade school and high school.
But if you look back on it, I could have done better.
I guess we all can look back and see that.
Were you involved in a lot of organizations?
In high school, I became involved in a few things, but not much.
And the reason was that I was riding a school bus from here
Actually, this property of ours, our home, is in the Kemp School District.
But because my mother taught in Kauffman and my father attended there, they guided us to Kauffman for high school.
And about the time I started, my two older brothers stayed with my uncle during the week when they went to high school.
But when I started, the bus service started.
And when it rained,
You and I went over that tree, limb-covered road across Walnut Creek.
When it rained, I had to walk from here on another mile from where you and I turned around.
So you had a good walk.
So I had no time for after school.
I tried football, for example, and there was no way in the world for me to get back and forth with football.
Now, my older brother, Walter, was a very fine football player, but he lived with his uncle, and he could do that.
I had really very few activities as extracurricular activities.
I was president of my junior class, and I was a salutatorian of my senior class in high school.
When I got to A&M, of course, I did get involved in quite a number of activities.
Would you consider yourself as president of your junior class in high school?
A leader?
I think so.
I don't think we were as conscious of it then.
I think popularity had a lot to do with it, but I think respect had more.
And if I'm correct in that, I guess there's some leadership reflection there.
Were you popular?
Well, I was well-liked, I think.
But you were respected then?
I think so.
And it was a combination of those two that resulted in...
Yes, of course, when you say you respected, there are a number of things behind that.
Oh, sure.
You say, sure, like personality and achievement, conduct.
Because I'm always wondering when leaders began...
feeling like they're leaders or begin taking the responsibility of leadership roles.
And I find that while I'm talking to different generals, some of them didn't start until their 20s, and some of them always remember taking that responsibility even when they were teenagers.
I was wondering when you first started taking the responsibilities of a leader.
Well, I guess that was it.
I think you're entirely right in this search for leadership characteristics.

Certainly one that the Army and the other armed forces have given a great deal of study and attention to, trying to understand this and trying to determine how you can place your bets on these young people that come into the Army.
Sure.
I think you're right.
We can take ten people and their leadership ability has probably surfaced at different
stages depending upon or being determined by the experiences and the tests that they were put to.

I recall after World War II I came to A&M for duty on the military staff there, and I remember when we were at summer camp with our cadets, the Department of the Army sent a team down to try to determine

criteria for leadership and see if they could measure it in those cadets and of course all of the officers such as such as I were interviewed our ideas sought and so forth well I had World War II under my belt not a lot of years in the service but a lot quite a lot of experience but I said then and I believe today that leadership really in terms of military leadership
is acquired by a series of successful experiences, the little ones building to bigger ones, and then you really know whether you've got it or not.
Let me interrupt just for one minute.
Do you like chicken curry?
I love it.
Do you?
I do.
You know, I think maybe I'll just whip up some curry and have some salad and then just stay home.
Okay.
Because Ken's going to be late.
Fine.
Are you sure you like it?
I love curry.
Good.
Of course, that leadership ability is built on experience.
Of course, you've got to have certain inherent capabilities to keep moving up that line of success in experience.
You started taking on the role later when you were a teenager.
I would say that that was on the bottom of the rungs of this experience ladder, yes.
Did you have a definite set of aims when you graduated from high school?
I really did not in terms of specifics.
I had these aims.
One aim was to get a good college education.
And I felt that would lead me to a further definition of my aims.
And I think it did.
Unfortunately or unfortunately, World War II interrupted the chain of events.
And as you know, my class of 41, A&M, were all called to active duty on graduation.
But that was my primary goal, was to get a good college education.
But after that, it was pretty vague.
Well, in terms of generalities, I wanted to be a success at whatever I engaged in.
But you didn't know what field.
I majored in marketing and finance at A&M, and I wanted to get into banking.
I had been accepted for employment in the Federal Land Bank in Houston upon graduation with the
the prospect, I'd be too strong to say a promise, that I would be trained in all departments before I was finally placed.
In other words, I would be what they call these days, and we didn't hear the term then, was a junior executive trainee.
Well, that suited me just fine.
But of course, I never went to that job because I was ordered to active duty.
How about the Depression?
In what way did the Depression, which you grew up with during the Depression, in what way did that have an impact on your life?
Well, of course, I remember that vividly.
I was about 10 years old when that started.
And I guess the main impression that it made on me, I didn't suffer, really, as a youngster.
because we were fortunate.
We never were hungry or lacked the essentials, you know, food, shelter, and clothing.
The luxuries, which we never really partook of anyway, before or after, to any great extent, were not missed.
I guess the main impression I got was what a tough thing this was on the people who were responsible for families
My parents and my friends' parents, our friends and neighbors, and family, you know, uncles and so forth.
Sure, absolutely.
And, of course, it had to create wonderment as to how can this happen?
You know, just a kid, you have no capability to analyze it, but you sure can ask the question.
And I guess that...
One of my impressions was that I never want this to happen to me.
In my family.
You know, as an adult.
And what kind of action did you take to free yourself?
Well, that's just more inspiration to succeed.
To take life seriously.
To meet...
Of course, as youngsters, your goals are set out for you by your parents if they're doing their job, and mine were.
But when you take off for university, then you're on your own.
You've got to make your own objectives and thereafter.
Of course, this is during the New Deal, Franklin Roosevelt, so I was wondering what political persuasion your father was and what one you came to accept.
My father was a very
loyal Democrat.
Of course, in those days, Republicans were still carpetbaggers.
When I left the Army, and until I left the Army, I was never active in politics at all.
In fact, I don't think I really, I always felt professional military people were outside the realm of politics.
Now, the franchise, the vote's important, but I never really
felt that I needed that, except wartime I liked to vote who was going to lead us.
Who did you vote for then during the war?
Well, I always voted for Roosevelt.
I think he was a great war leader.
And of course, at that time we had our great Sam Rayburn, Speaker of the House, and he and my father were friends, by the way.
Sam Rayburn knew all the
community leaders in his district.
Anyway, I was not conscious of politics, ever really, until as I was winding up my military career.
My last assignment was as chief of legislative liaison for the Army, which meant I was the senior liaison officer with the Congress.
This, for the first time, gave me very close association and view of the federal government, and specifically the Congress.
I'm still shocked to hear people in my present environment sound off about how lousy those members of Congress are, and they're all crooks.
But I came away from that experience with a much enhanced
regard for the total system of our government that our Constitution writers set up and a much more aware appreciation of the Congress as a as an institution and of the individuals in the Congress.
They're among the most among the hardest working people I've ever known and for the most part extremely conscientious people.
I have taken the
the liberty to rebut some of these comments about our government and our congressmen.
But, of course, in this country, we all have the right to say these things.
We're very prone to do it because we hired them, you know.
Oh, yeah, right.
But I say if you threw a fishnet around 100 guys in Kauffman and then took a look at each one of them individually, there'd be some of them you'd want to throw back.
There's going to be two or three of them.
that you'd rather not net.
And I think it's about the same measure in Congress.
We just hear so much about those who do stray and err and show up to be crooks or immoral.
There are not many of them.
No.
Were you ever a member of a political party then?
Well, when I did leave the Army and had that experience with the Congress, I felt very strongly that
Every citizen should get involved because politics is defined as the art of governing, and we're supposed to govern ourselves.
If we can't contribute to it, we have no right to make that criticism or complain about conditions as they are.
But I became a Democrat because, well, you might say my heritage was that, and I'd always felt associated with it, although I was never active before.

sometimes I wonder and I guess we all do whether I should say I'm a Democrat or join the Republican Party because on some issues I'm very much on that side other issues I think my party that I've chosen to support is correct I basically feel that
It's not right to call yourself an independent because we do have a two-party system and I think it's very important to us.
And as a matter of fact, I regret now that the Republicans didn't gain control of the House of Representatives so that they would control the White House and the Senate and the House.
Just as I felt that while Mr. Carter was not my choice,
and among the nominees to be president or candidate for the Democratic Party.

Once he was nominated, as far as I was concerned, he looked acceptable, and I supported him, and I knew it was impossible to have a Republican Congress, so no one really, it just makes sense, let's get one party responsible.
And if they don't hack it, then the other party has the absolute right to be elected.
to have their hand in it.
Well, the Republicans almost did, and I wish they had, because then they'd have full responsibility for the leadership of the government.
So in 1976, then, you supported Jimmy Carter, and then in 1980, you supported Ronald Reagan?
That's right.
I think Mr. Carter failed.
The reason I feel that one party feels so strongly one party should control the federal government
We had two terms of, well, Mr. President Eisenhower had a Democratic Congress.
President Nixon had a Democratic Congress.
I saw President Nixon's administration at first hand.
And I think that division is very bad for us, that division of responsibility, with one party responsible for making the laws and another party responsible for carrying them out.
And look at what's going on in the House of Representatives today.
foot dragging in me, or simply to express an individuality of view.
And I think Democrats are good people, but I think it's time that the Republicans run this thing and be responsible for it.
Sure.
For the good and the bad.
Yes, sir.
I'm somewhat confused then.
Would you say that you're a conservative or a moderate or a liberal?

How would you define your personal... Well, I don't think that's very hard to do because if you just look at the last ten years since I've been, shall we say, exercising my franchise to vote and participate in politics...
the color of conservatives has changed a great deal.
And on the other hand, liberals, we don't see near as much evidence of the liberals today as we did two Congresses ago, when we swept in a whole huge numbers of young liberals.
I don't think that's a fair way to do it.
I think that the conditions in the country change, and I think

the things that are important to me are very important to me is of course first of all national security you would expect that given my career and so I spend a great deal of time excuse this throat I don't know why I'm getting all tangled up here well let me finish this I am a great

conservative when it comes to national security because I think that we're gambling with the security of this nation to adopt a strategy as did President Kennedy and Johnson with Robert McNamara, Secretary of Defense, that being equal is good enough.
I know it's awfully hard to determine when you're equal or you're superior or you're
But we cannot gamble with the... Somebody's got to make that judgment, and we cannot gamble with the security of this nation.
So I'm very conservative on that issue.
I think our international relations are, of course, allied to this very, very closely.
And so international affairs are of great interest to me.
And I don't know what's a conservative in international affairs or what's a liberal.
But if being conservative is to resist the very thought of any further communist encroachment into the Western hemisphere, then I'm a conservative.
The people who say let the Central Americans determine their own fate down there, I've served in Latin America, and I know how these are determined.
And I think we're stupid if we let that happen.
We've got to influence it, and we've got to influence it in our favor for our future as a nation and for the future of our people.
Somewhere in here, economics stands right up alongside these things.
In fact, they're the base from which the strength flows for national security and an effective foreign policy.
So are you conservative or liberal on economics?
So on economics, I'm liberal in the sense of opening trade.
I don't believe in tariffs, barriers.
I really don't believe in subsidies for international trade, but that's very common throughout the world.
What about subsidies for farm products?
I don't believe in subsidies as such for farm products.
I would rather, and I believe most people in agriculture, and I'm just dabbling in it, would much rather see a free up of the markets plus the knowledge that they can get a federal
federally guaranteed loan if they just looked too bad on the books for the bankers to say, I can't do it because bank regulations won't let me.
I think most farmers would be happy with that.
So I guess I'm a moderate, I guess, because somewhere in the middle is the average of my views.
I only forgot one thing.
That's social legislation or social programs.
Do you consider yourself a moderate?
I would say I'm a moderate on social legislation.
legislation or social programs.
I think we've gone far overboard.
But I think that, for example, I think Social Security is a fine thing.
It's a must.
But I believe also that Mr. Reagan is correct, that he's gotten all out of focus.
It's become many things other than the intended floor
for the person who has to quit work or retire.
It's become an education vehicle for the kids.
It's become a disability compensation program.
It's become a very, very expensive thing.
Now, on other social programs, I believe that there should be some kind of a medical insurance program.
that protects every family or every individual from that disastrous illness.
But to be able to go to your doctor because you don't feel well and have the government pay for it, I don't believe in that.
I do believe because we certainly practice this in the military, but preventive health measures are much less expensive than that.
Corrective, just like preventive maintenance is better than mechanics repairs on your automobile.
But somewhere we've gone too far in this.
Medicaid, Medicare, and so forth.
I think it's too expensive.
Well, we're ready to start A&M, but first we're going to get some water for you.
Now, let's continue.
And I wanted to know if...
Why did you decide to go to A&M?
Here you have an older brother, one going to TCU, and one going to A&M.
Why A&M?
Probably because my older brother went there and was going there, and I had some good friends.
One of my closest friends went to A&M.
He was ahead of me a year in high school.
And to tell you the truth, I didn't study the field of universities available to me like youngsters do now.
Yeah.
A&M attracted my attention, and it seemed just the place I ought to go.
There were no other alternatives then, really?
I never really considered them.
And as a matter of fact, I had to wait a year after graduating high school before I'd go to A&M.
And then I wasn't sure I was going to be able to enroll that fall.
All of a sudden, Dad says, well, that's what's important.
You better get on down to A&M.
This is like a week before school started.
So this friend took me down, and there I was.
That year I was out of school, I should mention, was a very valuable year to me.
Because in those days, see, we were graduating high school at the age of 17.
We only had 11.
grades in school.
And I couldn't go to school for financial reasons.
And so I stayed out.
And that was the first year that Coffman High School offered what they call postgraduate courses, which I guess they now call continuing education.
And so I enrolled to keep active.
And I took bookkeeping, vocational agriculture,
Typing, I guess that was it.
And at the same time, you were living out here helping your father on the ranch?
Living out here helping my dad.
As a matter of fact, that cotton gin down there you saw, old building, that cotton gin was operating.
And dad hurt himself in that cotton gin.
He had an injury to his knee, and he was just laid up.
And I had to drop out of post-graduate school.
And I actually ran that cotton gin as manager and chief honcho for the rest of the season, about two and a half months.
And that was a very good experience.
I was responsible for keeping the books, collecting, paying the customer for his seed, and seeing that everybody was there for work, and we had what we needed and everything.
Very fine experience.
And that's why I mentioned to you earlier that I probably got more education
that year than any other year of my schooling.
That was a lot of responsibility for a 17-year-old.
Very good experience.
And how many people did you have working for you then?
The minimum crew down there was four more, four additional people, five additional people.
You had a man on the section, you had a fireman, you had a gym stand operator, and you had two people up in the press room.
So you were at 17.
You were in charge of five of them.
Of course, I grew up with that cotton gin.
I worked in there every year until we went to school.
In those days, too, we started school late so people couldn't have time to use the kids and get their crops in.
